      <trans-unit id="11127" identifier="aa633c06d096c5470f3d7b9afe8bc830">
        <source>Now you have added parity cards to make the number of black squares in every row and every column equal to an even number.
Don't point this out to the students at this stage.</source>
        <target>crwdns11127:0crwdne11127:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[35]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11128" identifier="db23b2a4bb407a3ad6cb9043dcb1cfd1">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns11128:0{panel end}crwdne11128:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[36]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11129" identifier="ea08f2f76d1ef4a9f87b3ba4c0221b4a">
        <source>Lesson activities</source>
        <target>crwdns11129:0crwdne11129:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 2&#13;
XPath: /h2[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11130" identifier="a48c859e06a354efcdd473f2ed3407a1">
        <source>Teacher to student: &quot;I'd like you flip over one card while I cover my eyes&quot;.</source>
        <target>crwdns11130:0crwdne11130:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[37]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11131" identifier="2babab2025d02942779db6ec62ce6382">
        <source>Teacher to class: &quot;Keep a close eye on which card it is to check if I have done my magic trick correctly!&quot;</source>
        <target>crwdns11131:0crwdne11131:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[38]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11132" identifier="8cf2c85a34aeca6366653a2038852ac9">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;teaching&quot; title=&quot;Teaching observations&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11132:0crwdne11132:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[39]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11133" identifier="e743357848a964649e90c8b28782ac5a">
        <source>You need to emphasise that you want just one card flipped over.</source>
        <target>crwdns11133:0crwdne11133:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[40]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11134" identifier="f792b5059e73dc639917ead8cfa1371c">
        <source>This prevents them from turning over too many cards (or none!).</source>
        <target>crwdns11134:0crwdne11134:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[40]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11135" identifier="0c8d866e12bbc75d9825367888f19661">
        <source>Usually students will follow this instruction, and their classmates will be able to confirm to you that, or let you know if one hasn't been turned over yet.</source>
        <target>crwdns11135:0crwdne11135:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[40]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11136" identifier="5da2b7782a8a36ff79379114a236578c">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns11136:0{panel end}crwdne11136:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[41]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11137" identifier="528d63e1c08697fed2e768dfe0f43630">
        <source>After the class confirms that a single card has been flipped, turn around to look at the cards.</source>
        <target>crwdns11137:0crwdne11137:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[42]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11138" identifier="18d69de551c3663cac6b43abd5e7a053">
        <source>Scan the cards looking for the row with an odd number of black squares, and the column that has an odd number of black squares.</source>
        <target>crwdns11138:0crwdne11138:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[42]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11139" identifier="0869dc56ba4e93756cc48d78344c1154">
        <source>The card that has been flipped will be at the intersection of these two lines.</source>
        <target>crwdns11139:0crwdne11139:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[42]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11140" identifier="6653dc343a1a06f439cc6dab0d3a7ced">
        <source>Turn this card over casually to restore it to the correct colour, saying “it’s this one”.</source>
        <target>crwdns11140:0crwdne11140:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[42]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11141" identifier="c3a604d877040a6556cea8f0881c4f67">
        <source>You can make a fuss that it might have been a fluke, so repeat the trick again.
(After you put the card back to how it was originally, look away again and ask for another card to be flipped over.)</source>
        <target>crwdns11141:0crwdne11141:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[43]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11142" identifier="20b4a9a644f13afcbc5bdf84faaf1f9a">
        <source>{image file-path=&quot;img/topics/parity-wizard.png&quot; alt=&quot;A wizard holding a magic one with parity cards on it.&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11142:0crwdne11142:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[44]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11143" identifier="811921fd0006478bbdbeb5732c07d070">
        <source>So is it magic? Or is it a trick?</source>
        <target>crwdns11143:0crwdne11143:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[45]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11144" identifier="76d062ad6de73423e4245e165510516b">
        <source>Teacher to class: &quot;Let’s first look at the cards before one was turned over&quot; (make sure you've restored the card that was just flipped).</source>
        <target>crwdns11144:0crwdne11144:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[46]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11145" identifier="81f68635acb17db4770ae4a466f9fc79">
        <source>The following steps will help the students to uncover what you've done:</source>
        <target>crwdns11145:0crwdne11145:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[46]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11146" identifier="64c8616cc578ee50b72e1972df8b72c6">
        <source>&quot;Are there any patterns you can see? Think, pair, share.&quot;</source>
        <target>crwdns11146:0crwdne11146:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[3]/li</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11147" identifier="62c12a065aecc24fa89dff64752015ab">
        <source>&quot;Let’s break it down into parts&quot;</source>
        <target>crwdns11147:0crwdne11147:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[3]/li[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11148" identifier="36a0893b2eda3707d90680adfdeb6ab3">
        <source>&quot;Let’s look at the first row - count the black squares - how many are there?&quot; (4 in the example above)</source>
        <target>crwdns11148:0crwdne11148:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[3]/li[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11149" identifier="60ca57a65db8f05611be74f0cb764375">
        <source>&quot;Now the second row - count the black squares - how many are there?&quot; 2</source>
        <target>crwdns11149:0crwdne11149:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[3]/li[4]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11150" identifier="d62cf34db4fd810f941fd5a2ecdc9499">
        <source>Note that it could be a row of all white squares - which would be 0 black squares; or it could be a row of all black squares - 6</source>
        <target>crwdns11150:0crwdne11150:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[3]/li[5]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11151" identifier="86833066d5ff5fd6b25a746c9d7ba8ba">
        <source>Teacher to class: “If we group these numbers together, 0, 2, 4, 6, what do we call this group?
Even numbers.
What about 1, 3, 5?
What is the name for this group of numbers?
Odd numbers.</source>
        <target>crwdns11151:0crwdne11151:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[47]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11152" identifier="9a4306c7d42b4e40042347e079e90a78">
        <source>Let’s now look at the columns:</source>
        <target>crwdns11152:0crwdne11152:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[48]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11153" identifier="112e02addcff01d35b44303725284833">
        <source>&quot;Does the first column have the same rule as the rows?&quot;.</source>
        <target>crwdns11153:0crwdne11153:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[4]/li</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11154" identifier="d47fccc32e1f669e92d84abb37863a4c">
        <source>&quot;What about the other columns?&quot;.</source>
        <target>crwdns11154:0crwdne11154:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[4]/li[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11155" identifier="2d70766c439a1e5370d6990646b48902">
        <source>Teacher to class: “So how did we end up with an even number in every row and column - did the volunteer choose that?” (they didn't!).</source>
        <target>crwdns11155:0crwdne11155:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[49]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11156" identifier="88d330ee03066335baf68fe0497d198e">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;teaching&quot; title=&quot;Teaching observations&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11156:0crwdne11156:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[50]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11157" identifier="64af2eec769792e57351904f2bd4a4f8">
        <source>Break these steps down to what is appropriate for your groups numeracy knowledge.</source>
        <target>crwdns11157:0crwdne11157:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[51]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11158" identifier="87be98beaeacdbb19d6e36a85ae885b7">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns11158:0{panel end}crwdne11158:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[52]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11159" identifier="e7c7af95254e8636340189a144ca5e3b">
        <source>Remove your extra row and column, and have them explain what colour to place at the end of the first row to make sure there is an even number of black cards.</source>
        <target>crwdns11159:0crwdne11159:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[53]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11160" identifier="e80b4cf7a88f9cad5eb78c82bad1bca3">
        <source>For example, if there are 3 black cards, ask what colour you need to add to make it into an even number (black)?</source>
        <target>crwdns11160:0crwdne11160:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[53]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11161" identifier="ef54c480b066f7d652bd678239a9d5d5">
        <source>If there are 4 black cards, they should work out that you need a white card to keep it even.</source>
        <target>crwdns11161:0crwdne11161:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[53]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11162" identifier="fdef34a55727a1c467d6c78afb4a5745">
        <source>Continue doing this for each row; then do it for the columns.</source>
        <target>crwdns11162:0crwdne11162:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[54]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11163" identifier="5783f976ff57dbbb5fc3c1f30647abc9">
        <source>This is a good exercise for students thinking about even and odd numbers.</source>
        <target>crwdns11163:0crwdne11163:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[54]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11164" identifier="ad80d8a1e4c160af3ed929ae235db4d2">
        <source>For the last (corner) card, ask if you should use the row or column to decide it.</source>
        <target>crwdns11164:0crwdne11164:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[54]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11165" identifier="d7e884e9337f094da25280c59c76cb12">
        <source>They should observe that it's the same for both.</source>
        <target>crwdns11165:0crwdne11165:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[54]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11166" identifier="8195489d5cfa2293178233ced2ceec43">
        <source>Once the extra row and column have been added, ask “So what happens when I turn a card over from black to white?” (It reduces the number of black cards by one, so it's now an odd number).</source>
        <target>crwdns11166:0crwdne11166:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[55]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11167" identifier="5ab93a62c9e748be9297d47a5a62f4e5">
        <source>&quot;What if I change a white card to black?&quot; (it adds one, which also gives an odd number).</source>
        <target>crwdns11167:0crwdne11167:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[55]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11168" identifier="3e82f00056094813a17ac1a8b29affe5">
        <source>The students might work out from this how to find the flipped card, but in either case, have a student come up, and ask them to look away while you flip a card.</source>
        <target>crwdns11168:0crwdne11168:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[56]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11169" identifier="bdc9738955c9b148519bc417775c681b">
        <source>Then, when they look back, ask &quot;Is the first row ok?&quot; (They should notice that it's still even, so hasn't been changed).</source>
        <target>crwdns11169:0crwdne11169:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[56]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11170" identifier="cb3604eedeeff1364078e806686aeb01">
        <source>Carry on for each row until they identify the one with an odd number of black cards.</source>
        <target>crwdns11170:0crwdne11170:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[56]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11171" identifier="2c13bf6d68d5640eecf9bb678ef3230f">
        <source>Draw a box around that row, and say &quot;So one of these cards was flipped?&quot;
Now do the same with the columns - ask if each one is correct, then draw around the column that they identify.</source>
        <target>crwdns11171:0crwdne11171:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[56]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11172" identifier="899d1edb48084aac50553473d499c298">
        <source>Now ask &quot;So which card was flipped?&quot; Usually students will identify the one at the intersection.</source>
        <target>crwdns11172:0crwdne11172:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[57]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11173" identifier="aa3d5fb1c37384e7cffec3ee1545d8fc">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;teaching&quot; title=&quot;Teaching observations&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11173:0crwdne11173:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[58]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11174" identifier="170cd93b22bbd912283035722641c4e6">
        <source>Students have now worked out for themselves how this works.
The key idea is that we just added a little more data, but could reconstruct the original if one card was changed.</source>
        <target>crwdns11174:0crwdne11174:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[59]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11175" identifier="5b1b66dde85cd99677d4e459730556a3">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns11175:0{panel end}crwdne11175:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[60]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11176" identifier="20400ae131b745536b72b5558d86ffec">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;math&quot; title=&quot;Mathematical links&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11176:0crwdne11176:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[61]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11177" identifier="82b7e4e8a05d064b818258262bbcbe6f">
        <source>It also exercises the idea of grids (you can use phrases like &quot;5 by 5&quot;) and the language of columns and rows.</source>
        <target>crwdns11177:0crwdne11177:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[62]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11178" identifier="02ba9cf0718349a4e5923e19a78ec919">
        <source>For junior students there are a lot of opportunities to practise counting to 5 and recognising the patterns of even and odd numbers.</source>
        <target>crwdns11178:0crwdne11178:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[63]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11179" identifier="653de8c738fe1662cb2a391ce582df0b">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns11179:0{panel end}crwdne11179:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[64]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11180" identifier="93f7f710b96d25060d8fc0fdd8426091">
        <source>Applying what we have just learnt</source>
        <target>crwdns11180:0crwdne11180:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 2&#13;
XPath: /h2[4]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11181" identifier="d012b220edf914463007eea33571f855">
        <source>This kind of method is applied to almost all data that is stored or transmitted on computers (although usually a more sophisticated method is used that is even more reliable).</source>
        <target>crwdns11181:0crwdne11181:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul[5]/li</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11182" identifier="dde76d718c706e260b544950a8c613f6">
        <source>If we didn’t have error detection and correction then unexpected errors in data would be common, and digital devices wouldn't be used to store anything important.</source>
        <target>crwdns11182:0crwdne11182:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul[5]/li</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11183" identifier="fcf882eef821d2fb947f3ed993a969cf">
        <source>The world would be in chaos and people wouldn’t trust computers.</source>
        <target>crwdns11183:0crwdne11183:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul[5]/li</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11184" identifier="3ec6eab150e59ce53ae63e7cc574731f">
        <source>Computers wouldn’t be reliable.</source>
        <target>crwdns11184:0crwdne11184:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul[5]/li</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11185" identifier="5311c0a11d8a89cf34e606aa8efb59d7">
        <source>DVDs and CDs wouldn’t work if one fleck of dust was on the disc.</source>
        <target>crwdns11185:0crwdne11185:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[5]/li[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11186" identifier="019b79b12ffdc15ed146bdf0e8dad207">
        <source>Backing up wouldn't help much as this would also be unreliable too.</source>
        <target>crwdns11186:0crwdne11186:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[5]/li[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11187" identifier="3fb6b225c7fcf852c74dfa78944da35b">
        <source>Transmitting data over long distances (e.g. from space probes) would be particularly unreliable, since it can take minutes, or even days, for data to arrive, and it's not feasible to request it to be retransmitted if it has had interference.</source>
        <target>crwdns11187:0crwdne11187:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[5]/li[4]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11188" identifier="5130654c0e861f29672a02e1d1360b7f">
        <source>Lesson reflection</source>
        <target>crwdns11188:0crwdne11188:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 2&#13;
XPath: /h2[5]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11189" identifier="7ac4119d5113e8d1d47058b67cae1fa0">
        <source>If each square was a piece of information sent to the computer and there wasn’t any parity data added to it, could the information be received correctly from one computer to another if one of the pieces of data is changed?</source>
        <target>crwdns11189:0crwdne11189:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[65]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11190" identifier="a10b261ebad875ce9b3f1f2dce1c04f0">
        <source>It can’t because if just one piece of information is incorrect then you have no way of knowing.</source>
        <target>crwdns11190:0crwdne11190:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[65]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11191" identifier="037b146985157d79e1e21ce7f0c43b77">
        <source>But when we add the parity data to the information, even if one small piece of information is incorrect (turned off instead of on) then the computer can correct the information and can read it properly.</source>
        <target>crwdns11191:0crwdne11191:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[65]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11192" identifier="612e302823043220d34b9c985a047e6d">
        <source>You could try using other objects.</source>
        <target>crwdns11192:0crwdne11192:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[66]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11193" identifier="5800b0269f84ca18da05a93aa15e98d2">
        <source>Anything that has two easily distinguished ‘states’ is suitable.</source>
        <target>crwdns11193:0crwdne11193:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[66]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11194" identifier="4f9c2f489682455b22e3eebda79c9460">
        <source>For example, you could use playing cards, coins (heads or tails) or counters with two different colours on each side.</source>
        <target>crwdns11194:0crwdne11194:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[66]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11195" identifier="99489a1118cca59df0f1f0d22eda7cab">
        <source>What happens if two, or more, cards are flipped?</source>
        <target>crwdns11195:0crwdne11195:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[67]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11196" identifier="3e7f6a32fb6282b47514bc152179e2c8">
